ENTRY 1: BISS FRAMEWORK MODERNISATION
================================================================================

CSI ID: BISS-AUTO-2026-001

Improvement Summary:
BISS Test Automation Framework Modernisation — Migrated 135+ legacy hard-coded 
test scenarios into a data-driven, self-healing BDD framework. Eliminated 90+ 
copy-pasted login blocks by centralising a shared Background. Consolidated 405 
UI locators into one ObjectRepository. Implemented runtime herd/agent selection 
from two live Oracle databases (BISS_DATA + BISS_INET) via HikariCP pooling. 
Built 6-layer resilience system (smart waits, dropdown self-heal, expired-agent 
recovery, blacklist re-fetch, scenario retry, soft assertions). Automated 
nightly Jenkins execution on OpenShift with pass/fail reporting.

Problem / Opportunity:
Legacy Cost: 4–6 hours per sprint on test maintenance (hand-editing hard-coded 
herd numbers, managing Excel row references, re-running on flaky failures). Tests 
contained placeholder assertions (masked values that could never fail), giving 
false-confidence passes in a government payment-validation process. Manual data 
preparation required before each run. No scheduled execution; results ad-hoc and 
scattered. Risk: False negatives could hide real bugs in BISS (critical 
government process).

Suggested Action:
Refactor 135+ scenarios as business-language Gherkin (BDD); build two-database 
DBRouter for live herd resolution at @BeforeAll; implement recovery ladder 
(6 levels); centralise all locators; automate nightly Jenkins with 
HTML/Word/XML/email reporting; track maintenance time savings and data-prep 
elimination.

Status: ✅ Complete (March 2026) — Live on production Jenkins/OpenShift, nightly execution active

Owner: Aniket Pathare (QA Automation Engineer)

Date Raised: 2026-01-15

Target Date: 2026-03-31

Outcome / Notes:
Live on Jenkins/OpenShift since March 2026. Nightly 22:00 execution Mon–Fri. 
Stakeholders receive pass/fail reports in inbox automatically. Framework now 
scalable for new test areas (Staff portal, Overclaim, Dual Claim modules reuse 
same engine). Maintenance cost per screen change dropped 90%.

TIME SAVED: 6–9 hours/sprint = ~300 hours/year
Breakdown: 4–6 hrs/sprint (maintenance elimination) + 2–3 hrs/sprint (zero 
manual data prep) + nightly automation eliminates ad-hoc re-run requests.

Innovation Highlights:
• Zero hard-coded test data (all from live DB at runtime)
• 90+ login blocks → 1 Background (consolidated)
• 405 centralised locators (one screen change = one fix, not 50+)
• 6-layer self-healing (15× recovery attempts before failing)
• 4 report formats (HTML, Word, XML, email) automated per run


