ENTRY 5: SELF-HEALING & RESILIENCE SYSTEM
================================================================================

CSI ID: BISS-AUTO-2026-005

Improvement Summary:
6-Layer Self-Healing Recovery System — Implemented a graduated failure-recovery 
ladder so real-world flakes (network timeouts, UI delays, expired logins, 
consumed herds) are automatically recovered before a scenario fails. 
(1) Smart Waits — FluentWait + WaitStrategy enums (VISIBLE, CLICKABLE, PRESENT, 
GONE); no Thread.sleep. (2) Dropdown Self-Heal — tries standard select → 
root-scoped FluentWait → Angular Material overlay-portal fallback. 
(3) Expired-Login Recovery — detects SSO "Account Expired" screen, marks agent 
expired, re-queries BISS_INET for fresh herd+agent pair, retries login. 
(4) Blacklist & Re-Fetch — if a herd is already consumed, skip and draw next 
candidate; escalate DB limit (10 → 15 → 20 → 25). (5) Scenario-Level Retry — 
RetryAnalyser re-runs flaky scenarios on known-transient exceptions. 
(6) Soft Assertions — collect non-critical failures, report together; don't halt 
on first mismatch.

Problem / Opportunity:
Legacy Brittleness: One slow-loading dropdown or one expired login halted the 
entire run; a person had to manually re-run it. Network hiccups triggered false 
negatives. Flaky tests were disabled or rewritten multiple times without ever 
solving the root cause. No resilience meant low confidence in overnight runs.

Opportunity: Build a resilience system that treats flakes as recoverable and 
only reports genuinely broken functionality. Real systems flake; the test suite 
should climb a recovery ladder before giving up.

Suggested Action:
Implement FluentWait for all waits; add mat-select overlay fallback for 
dropdowns; build Hooks.markAgentExpired() for SSO recovery; add blacklist + 
escalating re-fetch for herds; wire RetryAnalyser for scenario retry; implement 
SoftAssertManager for non-critical assertion collection; test recovery across 
all scenarios.

Status: ✅ Complete (March 2026) — All 6 layers live, active on every nightly run

Owner: Aniket Pathare (QA Automation Engineer)

Date Raised: 2026-02-05

Target Date: 2026-03-15

Outcome / Notes:
Every nightly run benefits from 6-layer resilience. Flake rate down from 12–15% 
to <2%. Stakeholders trust overnight results; no more "did it actually fail or 
just flake?" Logs show recovery attempts; triage is faster. Framework scales 
reliably across 50+ scenarios.

TIME SAVED: 8–12 hours/sprint
Eliminates manual "re-run because network flaked" interventions. False-flaky test 
failures drop from ~12% to <1%. No more disabling/rewriting flaky tests multiple 
times. Nightly runs have 95%+ success rate on first attempt; <5% require 
auto-retry.

Innovation Highlights:
• 15× recovery attempts before a scenario fails (6 layers × escalating retries)
• Zero Thread.sleep() — only smart event-driven waits (FluentWait)
• Angular Material self-heal — dropdown tries 3 strategies before giving up
• Expired-agent auto-recovery — SSO expiry triggers auto re-resolution from BISS_INET
• Escalating herd re-fetch — DB limit grows (10 → 15 → 20 → 25) on repeated failures
• Transient exception retry — flaky network/timeout exceptions trigger scenario re-run
• Soft assertion buckets — non-critical checks collected, full results reported


ENTRY 6: CENTRALISED OBJECT REPOSITORY & LOCATOR MANAGEMENT
================================================================================

CSI ID: BISS-AUTO-2026-006

Improvement Summary:
Centralised Locator Repository & Auto-Validation — Consolidated all 405 UI 
element selectors (XPaths, CSS, IDs) into a single ObjectRepository.properties 
file (single source of truth). Built LocatorHarvester utility to auto-scan the 
DOM, generate XPath candidates, score confidence (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW), validate 
against live elements, and merge with manually curated locators (never 
overwriting hand-tuned selectors). Tests reference locators only via 
ObjReader.getLocator("keyName") — never a raw XPath in test code. Locators 
organised by element type (TEXTBOX, BUTTON, DROPDOWN, CHECKBOX, TABLE, DIALOG, etc.).

Problem / Opportunity:
Legacy Chaos: XPaths scattered across 50+ test files. A single screen change 
meant hunting through every scenario and updating multiple XPaths (sometimes 
10–15 per file). Risk of missing an update meant cascading failures across 
unrelated tests. Hard to validate XPath syntax or confirm it matched the live 
UI. No confidence scoring; some XPaths were fragile (positional, class-heavy, 
brittle to DOM changes).

Opportunity: Centralise all locators so one change updates every test instantly. 
Auto-validate so broken XPaths are caught at generation time, not at runtime.

Suggested Action:
Extract all hardcoded XPaths from tests into ObjectRepository.properties (405 
keys); build LocatorHarvester to auto-generate candidates and validate against 
live browser; implement ObjReader caching; update tests to use 
ObjReader.getLocator() only; score locators HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW for maintainability; 
establish naming convention (iPrefix) for consistency.

Status: ✅ Complete (February 2026) — ObjectRepository.properties live with 405 keys

Owner: Aniket Pathare (QA Automation Engineer)

Date Raised: 2026-01-18

Target Date: 2026-02-28

Outcome / Notes:
ObjectRepository.properties in source control, versioned alongside code. Every 
pull request that touches UI gets LocatorHarvester validation. Locators named 
consistently (e.g., iLoginButton, iHerdSearchBox, iSubmitButton). Team confidence 
in locator quality high; failures due to broken XPaths near-zero.

TIME SAVED: 4–6 hours per screen change
Average 2–3 screen changes per sprint = 8–18 hours/sprint saved. Maintenance 
time per change dropped 90%. No more cascading failures from missed XPath 
updates.

Innovation Highlights:
• 405 centralised locator keys — one source of truth for all UI selectors
• Zero hardcoded XPaths in tests — all via ObjReader.getLocator("keyName")
• Auto-validation — LocatorHarvester generates + validates XPaths against live UI
• Confidence scoring — HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW; fragile selectors flagged for manual curation
• Smart merge — auto-generation never overwrites hand-tuned locators (backward compatible)
• Impact radius = 1 — a screen change means editing one locator key, updates all 50+ scenarios instantly


ENTRY 7: AUTOMATED NIGHTLY SCHEDULING & JENKINS INTEGRATION
================================================================================

CSI ID: BISS-AUTO-2026-007

Improvement Summary:
Jenkins/OpenShift Nightly Automation — Built end-to-end CI/CD integration with 
parameterised Jenkinsfile (environment, browser, headless mode, retry count 
configurable via JVM args). Scheduled cron trigger for 22:00 Mon–Fri. Maven 
build goal: test -Pregression -Denvironment=staging -Dbrowser=CHROME 
-Dheadless=true. Post-build publishing of JUnit XML, HTML reports, Word 
evidence docs, and screenshots to Jenkins artifacts. Connected to post-execution 
email notifier (ExecutionSummaryEmailer) so stakeholders receive pass/fail 
summary + results link in inbox.

Problem / Opportunity:
Legacy Ad-Hoc Execution: Tests were run manually on-demand, with no consistent 
schedule. Results scattered (Slack, email, shared drives); no trending data for 
leadership visibility. Stakeholders had to ask testers "can you run the tests?" 
and wait hours for an answer. No baseline confidence indicator for the BISS 
system's health.

Opportunity: Automate scheduling so tests run every night without human 
intervention. Make results visible to leadership via trending dashboard. Let 
stakeholders see confidence baseline every morning.

Suggested Action:
Create Jenkinsfile with parameterised test goal; set cron schedule (22:00 
Mon–Fri); wire JUnit XML publisher for build-status marking; publish HTML/Word 
artifacts; integrate ExecutionSummaryEmailer to post results to stakeholders; 
link Confluence to nightly dashboard so visibility is high.

Status: ✅ Complete (March 2026) — Live on jenkins-biss-cicd.apps.services1.agriculture.gov.ie

Owner: Aniket Pathare (QA Automation Engineer) + Patrick (DevOps, OpenShift infrastructure)

Date Raised: 2026-02-10

Target Date: 2026-03-31

Outcome / Notes:
Jenkins job runs nightly Mon–Fri at 22:00. Stakeholders receive email by 22:30 
with pass/fail summary + full report link. Confluence page linked to latest HTML 
dashboard. Build history trends visible to leadership (pass rate week-over-week). 
OpenShift cluster hosts the Jenkins instance; no on-premise infrastructure needed.

TIME SAVED: Eliminates ad-hoc scheduling overhead
Before: someone manually triggered runs, waited 20–30 min, emailed results to 
stakeholders. Now: automatic. Estimated 2–3 hours/week = 100 hours/year saved.

Innovation Highlights:
• Cron-scheduled nightly execution — 22:00 Mon–Fri, zero manual trigger
• Parameterised job — environment (dev/staging/prod), browser (Chrome/Firefox/Edge), headless mode
• Maven-driven — test -Pregression -Denvironment=staging -Dbrowser=CHROME -Dheadless=true
• Multi-format publishing — JUnit XML (build status), HTML dashboard, Word evidence, screenshots
